  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: d1d62931ab01cd14b84145ae3bdd017f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Chapter 4
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  chapter: 4
  levelTerms:
  - level: 15
    terms:
    - term: Mechanical Work
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Action of force, moving in certain direction, to an object
      details: "As defined in Mechanics, is an action of a force, moving in a certain
        direction, to an object. Meaning, work is achieved if the object is moving
        alongside the direction the force is directed at, or the object is moving
        at a component of the force\u2019s direction."
    - term: Work
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Observe the image at the left.
      details: The image is depicting a man performing push-up. Based on observation
        alone, he is applying force on the ground to push himself up a certain height,
        then goes down, then repeats the cycle all over again, until he eventually
        tires himself. Based from the question earlier, one can directly assume that
        he applies force to achieve a certain distance, which, in this case, is height.
        Applying a force over a certain distance is the simplest definition of work
    - term: Power
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: The computed amount of work done within a certain time.
      details: Its derived unit is the Watt (WW), named after the mechanical engineer
        James Watt. With that in mind, let us go back to the push-upexample. If he
        has done 267.48 joules of work within 30 seconds, we can compute for work
        using,
    - term: Formulas
      unit: 
      type: 2
      description: 'Work: W = Fx'
      details: 'F = force, x = fixed distance

'
  - level: 16
    terms:
    - term: Energy
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: property that objects need to trasnsfer in order to perform work
      details: Is best defined as the property that objects need to transfer in order
        to perform work. Since there is transfer involved, energy can neither be
        created nor destroyed. It can only change forms, which allows a body to perform
        work on another body. Its unit is also joule. But it can also be watt-second,
        watt-hour, horsepower-second, horsepower-hour, and so on
    - term: 'Kinetic Energy '
      unit: T
      type: 2
      description: Energy translated in motion
      details: As KE or T) is the energy translated in motion (i.e. it is the energy
        observed in motion). It is also best explained as the energy an object possesses
        because it is moving. In formula, it is expressed as,
    - term: 'Potential Energy '
      unit: U
      type: 2
      description: Energy observed from rest
      details: "Gravitational Potential Energy: \nU_g = mgy\nElastic Potential Energy:\nU_e
        = (1/2) kx^2\n"
    - term: Two forms of Potential Energy
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Potential energy stored due to change in height
      details: 'Gravitational Potential Energy

        - potential energy stored
        due to change in height


        Elastic Potential Energy

        - potential
        energy stored by object when pulled apart or compressed'
    - term: Law of Conservation of Energy
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: It only transders and changes form, from one body to another
      details: "This is one of the fundamental conservation laws \r\nin Physics that
        explains that the total energy of the \r\nsystem is constant, which helps
        us tackle problem solving. There are two classifications of force: conservative
        and non-conservative. A conservative force is a force whose work done between
        two given points is independent from the path taken by the work itself. It
        also implies that if potential energy can be associated to a force, that
        force is conservative. "
    - term: Two classifications of Force
      unit: 
      type: 1
      description: Independent from the path taken by work between two points
      details: 'Conservative Force

        - independent from the path taken by
        work between two points

        Non-Conservative Force

        - follows
        the path taken by work between two points

        - or if force cannot associate
        itself with potential energy

'
